text:
Bill is exactly right.

There are plenty of micro-explanations and micro-excuses for what happened in the presidential election of 2024.  And on the margins, any number of them—indeed, almost certainly, a combination of them—made the difference.  But their impact was only on the margins.  Don’t get me wrong—small margins and the factors that move them do matter, a lot, in elections—particularly in America in the 21st century.  They deserve careful analysis, but only to a point.  

For the bottom line is that these considerations are not what we must focus on first and foremost today.  What deserves the lion’s share of our attention are the facts that a major political party could have even considered nominating Trump despite his manifest criminality, moral depravity, psychological derangement, and cognitive deficiencies and deterioration—and that nearly half the country would have voted for him no matter what he did or said and no matter whom he had run against.  That was the ultimate problem in this election, and remains so. 

We suffer from a deep sickness in our national polity.  Far above all else, before it’s too late, thoughtful Americans of good faith must work together to confront, to better comprehend, and to ultimately address that grave and metastasizing ailment if our great experiment in self-governance is to survive.  Scapegoating and blame-assigning about anything else serves no end but to diminish our chances of overcoming our profound national moral crisis.

text:
Donald Trump's struggle and political success;

Donald Trump’s recent victory in the 2024 U.S. presidential election has marked a striking return to the political spotlight. As the 45th and now 47th president, Trump has broken the precedent of a non-consecutive presidential term—a feat not seen since Grover Cleveland in the 19th century. Trump’s campaign maintained a clear message: a promise to restrict immigration, rollback environmental policies, promote American manufacturing, and intensify the nationalist focus that defined his first term.

Key campaign themes included economic nationalism, particularly through tariffs and restrictions on imports. Trump argued that such policies would restore American jobs and protect industries that have suffered in recent decades. Despite concerns from economists who warn that such trade policies could harm the economy, Trump found support among voters from economically struggling, deindustrialized areas, and it was this backing that solidified his victory in critical battleground states.

A major component of Trump’s 2024 campaign was his strategic outreach through digital platforms and social media influencers. He leveraged support from prominent figures like Elon Musk, who played a substantial role in mobilizing young, male voters. Musk’s endorsement, along with substantial financial backing, boosted Trump's reach among younger demographics. This focus on connecting with younger voters through social media and podcasts allowed Trump to appeal to non-traditional conservative bases, making his campaign appear dynamic and in touch with the digital age.

In addition to his economic and digital strategies, Trump pledged to roll back many policies implemented after his first term. Environmental regulations and social policies were central targets, with Trump emphasizing a shift toward deregulation and the restriction of transgender rights, which has garnered both strong support and opposition. These policies were particularly resonant among his conservative base, which remains enthusiastic about a shift toward traditional values and reduced government intervention.

His running mate, Ohio Senator JD Vance, brought a complementary focus on American nationalism and anti-establishment sentiment. Vance, a newcomer to Trump’s campaign, is known for his critiques of globalization and the decline of American manufacturing—both of which were instrumental themes in Trump's overall platform. This team helped drive voter turnout in key states like Ohio and Pennsylvania.

Internationally, Trump’s win signals the potential for a shift in U.S. foreign policy. During his campaign, Trump indicated that he would revisit trade relations, particularly with China, and continue his approach of emphasizing “America First” policies that prioritize U.S. interests over global cooperation. Analysts predict that Trump's return to office could lead to a more isolationist stance, which could impact the U.S.’s position on global climate agreements, NATO commitments, and trade alliances.

Despite legal controversies and political polarization, Trump managed to solidify his appeal across a mix of traditional conservative groups and new supporters, culminating in a victory that reflects ongoing divides within American society. His second term is expected to further solidify his legacy, whether through policy changes, judicial appointments, or his handling of pressing domestic and international issues. As he prepares for his inauguration in 2025, Trump’s approach to governance will shape the next four years and potentially leave a lasting impact on the trajectory of American politics.

🟧 ExtraOrdinal Daily #44 | What will the Trump Future bring for Crypto?

Donald Trump’s re-election is expected to significantly impact U.S. crypto policy, marked by a shift toward regulatory leniency and industry growth. His administration plans to replace SEC Chair Gary Gensler, known for strict enforcement, with a more crypto-friendly figure. Dan Gallagher, Robinhood’s chief legal officer and former SEC commissioner, is a leading candidate, indicating a potential easing of regulations. Another name that has been floated was Mark, an attorney and republican government official who served as a Commissioner of the U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission since June 30, 2022. Hester Peirce, known as “Crypto Mom,” has declined the role but remains influential. Is has been suggested that the SEC could drop all their crypto cases, except for explicit criminal fraud related cases. Potential repeals of restrictive measures like SEC bulletin SAB 121 could enable traditional banks to offer crypto services and develop stablecoins.

Besides the president himself, crypto has seen an absolute tsunami of crypto-friendly candidates elected earlier this week. The positive effect of this blockchain wave could lay the foundation for true acceptance and adoption over the next four years. A key legislative focus is the “BITCOIN Act of 2024,” proposed by Senator Cynthia Lummis, to establish Bitcoin as a U.S. strategic reserve asset. Analysts suggest this move could drive institutional investment and push Bitcoin’s value to targets like $90,000 by year-end and $200,000 by 2025.

Trump’s pro-business stance promises reduced compliance hurdles for DeFi platforms and increased integration with traditional finance. This regulatory shift could enhance stablecoin adoption and elevate U.S. status as a global crypto leader, attracting institutional investment.

Post-election, Bitcoin ETFs, such as BlackRock’s IBIT, recorded significant inflows ($1.38 billion in a day), showcasing market optimism.

Economic strategies involving tax cuts and potential fiscal stimulus may benefit crypto as a hedge against inflation. Trump’s administration is poised to create a favourable environment for innovation, setting a precedent that could influence global policy and solidify the U.S. as a leading crypto hub.

🔶 Daily Alpha | Bitcoin Update, Better than OP_CAT?

A group of leading Bitcoin developers, including experts from StarkWare and Blockstream, has introduced a new method that could transform Bitcoin's programmability. In a paper titled "ColliderScript: Covenants in Bitcoin via 160-bit hash collisions," the team presented a way to implement covenants—conditional transactions—without needing a contentious soft fork.

Covenants could enable advanced wallet functions, secure vaults, and more efficient layer-2 protocols. Unlike previous proposals like OP_CTV by Jeremy Rubin and OP_CAT, which require changes to Bitcoin's core code, this new approach avoids such modifications. While promising, the technique remains computationally intensive and costly to execute.

Ethan Heilman, co-author of OP_CAT, collaborated with Victor Kobolov, Avihu Levy from StarkWare, and Andrew Poelstra of Blockstream. StarkWare noted the potential for optimization despite current limitations.

Robin Linus, known for BitVM projects, praised the idea's ingenuity but pointed out practical challenges, citing potential execution costs exceeding $10 million. This breakthrough could help Bitcoin close the functionality gap with Ethereum while maintaining its robust security.

Secret Service Significantly Upgrades Protection for Trump: 

In light of the Justice Department releasing charges in an Iranian plot to assassinate Trump, I'm getting questions about President-elect Trump's level of security after his big election win. 

Without providing too many details that could harm his security, he now really does have the full-package of Secret Service assets (minus the use of an Air  Force One-type military plane) that Acting Secret Service Dir. Ron Rowe has claimed he provided him after the Butler assassination attempt. Sources in the Secret Service community had disputed whether it was the full package before the election - but say now Trump really does have what he needs, calling the post-election upgrade "substantial." 

The upgrade includes having the White Hosue Communications Agency at Trump's disposal. The WHCA is staffed with military experts devoted to protecting all of Trump's and Vance's communications with the highest level of encryption. This is incredibly important considering the unprecedented level of hacking (that is still ongoing) by  Chinese operatives that has taken place during the campaign. Trump, J.D. Vance, and Kamala Harris, were among 40 U.S. politicians and officials who had their phones accessed in what Senate Intelligence Mark Warner called the worst case of hacking he's been briefed on during his entire tenure as chairman. 

Other security upgrades now that Trump is president-elect have to do with manpower and vehicles: Trump is now augmented with Presidential Protective Division (the most highly trained and elite) agents, supervisors, and vehicles. 

During the campaign, Trump had his regular Trump Detail agents AND a campaign shift. After the assassination attempt, Trump was upgraded to have senior experienced agents from PPD doing the lead for all major campaign rallies and outdoor rallies. 

The sites also had to have a PPD assistant senior agent in charge as the second supervisor to make sure everything was correct before his arrival, just as the Secret Service does on every presidential and vice presidential trip. Now all of Trump's events will have that same level of higher protection -- with additional highly trained agents. 

Other assets added to Mar-a-Lago include robot dogs patrolling the club's perimeter and other "enhancements," at his Trump Tower residence in New York City,  according to the Secret Service. 

Secret Service protection is automatically provided to the children and grandchildren of sitting presidents, but Trump's son Barron Trump began his freshman year at New York University with Secret Service protection.

Trump now also will have daily intelligence briefings provided to him as a matter of law. The briefings are summaries of coordinated through the Office of the Director of National Intelligence with contributions from the CIA and other members of the Intelligence Community. During the campaign, Trump also received a form of these ODNI briefings, which can contain classified material albeit with certain limits, but it was done only as a custom, continuing a tradition dating back to 1952 when outgoing President Harry S. Truman recognized the need to bring then-candidate Dwight Eisenhower up to speed well before Inauguration Day.

text:
Wrote a piece in @MessariCrypto's daily newsletter this morning about Solana's Endgame. Here is a snippet:

This week, markets rallied with BTC up 8%, ETH up 14%, and SOL up 15% following Trump’s election win, signaling potential easing on crypto regulation. Solana has now surpassed BNB as the fourth-largest digital asset. Optimism is high for a more crypto-friendly SEC chair, increased regulatory clarity, and a potential Solana ETF in the coming years, attracting more institutional capital. Three Solana ETF applications have already been submitted this year by @vaneck_us, @21Shares, and @CanaryFunds.

Solana’s ambitious vision, as outlined by @aeyakovenko , aims to make it competitive with centralized exchanges like Nasdaq, creating a globally synchronized network without arbitrage opportunities. Achieving this goal involves three key upgrades: Bankless Leaders, Asynchronous Execution (AE), and Multiple Concurrent Block Producers (MCBP):
- Bankless Leaders allow block production without executing all transactions, improving reliability.
- Asynchronous Execution separates consensus from execution, allowing validators to work in parallel, significantly boosting transaction speeds and user experience.
- MCBP would enable multiple leaders to produce blocks concurrently, increasing transaction capacity and resilience.
Anatoly aims to implement AE by 2025, setting the stage for MCBP afterward. While some in the ecosystem have raised concerns, recent regulatory momentum suggests a brighter future for Solana. For those interested in a technical deep dive, Helius previously released a deep dive on these topics, and we will be releasing a piece on the Solana VM in December.

text:
I want to address at length Jacob Hess’s article in the Des News saying that Trump supporters need to be kind to people who might be feeling hurt after the election.
The most important point is that I know Jacob personally, and I can say his intentions are good. He is trying to be a peacemaker and promote reconciliation, and this comes from a good heart. So please don’t go after Jacob – he is a good man.
And of course being kind and having charity is always good. As followers of Christ, we should do this.
But there are many, many things that Jacob misses in this article, and frankly he shows a very one-side view of politics that I simply cannot ignore. The whole tone of his article is that somehow Trump supporters are ignorant, mean people who need to be reminded to be nice or else they will become brown shirted nazis, and this simply cannot be allowed to pass without a response.
Here are a few points that Jacob needs to be reminded of:
--Trump is not unusually immoral or bad. Like all presidents, he has some unfortunate characteristics and many good ones. This also applies to Trump supporters. If you know anything at all about the history of presidents, it should become obvious that Trump is not unique in terms of his personal conduct, and the claims that he is are simply ignorant and need to stop.
--Trump has been harassed and persecuted by bad actors relentlessly since 2016, and ignoring this history is harmful to the republic.
--Obama mounted a coup attempt against his successor, which has never happened before.
--The Deep State immediately persecuted Trump and his cabinet members like Michael Flynn.
--The Russia collusion process was based on Democrat campaign research and was complete fiction, and after three years the special prosecutor had to admit there was nothing there, yet the media accused Trump of being a Russian stooge throughout his presidency and continues to do so today.
--Trump never arrested a single journalist or political opponent, even though a strong case could be made that at the very least Hillary Clinton should have been prosecuted for destroying evidence regarding her email server while Secretary of State.
--Both impeachment attempts were completely unprecedented in their lack of evidence of any actual crime and were clearly simply political persecution.
--The media invented lie after lie about Trump, especially the “many fine people hoax,” and they never apologized about it.
--The entire Jan. 6 debacle was planned and executed by the Deep State, with hundreds of FBI agents firing up the crowd and Capitol police deliberately opening doors to encourage people to go into the Capitol.
--When Trump was out of office the FBI was weaponized against him, raiding his private home with kill orders. Yes, kill orders.
--When Trump announced he would run for office again the Biden administration coordinated at least four completely baseless lawfare campaigns against Trump with the explicit intent of bankrupting him so he could not run for president.
--Trump was shot once and the government has completely covered up the investigation, and we still do not know what happened. The second attempt was carried out by a person with clear Deep State connections.
--Trump supporters were called Nazis, fascists, garbage and the media claimed there would never be another fair election. The media continues to fabricate lies about Trump – just to cite one example, we have the claim that Trump wanted to kill Liz Cheney with a firing squad, which was clearly mendacious.
--Yet, throughout all of this, Jacob somehow comes to the conclusion (without mentioning any of the history) that somehow it is incumbent on Trump supporters and Trump supporters only to reach out to console the losers, the same people who have lied, harassed, broken laws and tried to kill Trump without surcease since 2016.
Sorry, Jacob, I love you brother, but this is just a bridge too far.
This country needs justice. Many of these people need to be put in jail, not consoled.
And by the way, since when it is kind to help people maintain delusions that are clearly untrue?
